block.documentation:
The Guidance, Navigation, and Control (GN&C) Subsystem provides precise control over the AOMS’s orientation and trajectory. The subsystem is equipped with advanced sensors such as Star Trackers, a GPS Receiver, and an Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU), which work together to continuously determine the spacecraft's position and orientation relative to its orbital path. The Reaction Wheels and Magnetometers help maintain and adjust the spacecraft’s attitude, ensuring it remains in the correct orientation for solar power generation and communication with Earth.
The GN&C Control CSC manages the sensor data and calculates the necessary adjustments to maintain or correct the spacecraft’s orientation. It interfaces with the Propulsion Subsystem when more significant orbital adjustments are needed, ensuring that the AOMS stays in its designated orbit and performs necessary maneuvers, such as collision avoidance. This subsystem ensures the spacecraft remains stable, aligned, and operational throughout its mission.
